A few smells:

- Singleton Configuration
- Singletons
- Verbose Naming
- Noisy Logging
	- we log everything
	- so you log the act of logging?
	- no, that would be silly! ...
	- so you log that assigment there?
	- no...
- log and throw
- repetition and duplication
- unnecessary code
- mixed levels of abstraction
	- business logic
	- bitshifting
	- socket connection
- legacy coding habits
- programming by coincidence
- programming by superstition

"Stringly typed language/system"

Poor code is seldom malicious, stupid or random. Pick a set of axioms ('style guides'), and the poor code will follow systematically.

If you can't construct the object, don't return an invalid object — throw. ("That's why constructors were originally created".)

